    <AccordionItem>
      <svelte:fragment slot="summary">Owner's Policies</svelte:fragment>
      <svelte:fragment slot="content">A homeowner’s policy protects you, the purchaser, against potential losses stemming from faults in your ownership or interest in the property. Safeguarding the equity in your new home necessitates obtaining a title policy.

Standard title insurance coverage addresses risks such as:

Forgery and impersonation
Lack of competency, capacity, or legal authority of a party
Deed not signed by a necessary party (co-owner, heir, spouse, corporate officer, or business partner)
Undisclosed (yet recorded) prior mortgage or lien
Undisclosed (yet recorded) easement or use restriction
Erroneous or inadequate legal description
Lack of a right of access
Deed not correctly recorded
An Enhanced Owner’s Policy offers extended coverage to safeguard against additional defects such as:

Off-record matters, including claims for adverse possession or prescriptive easement
Deed to land with buildings encroaching on land owned by another
Incorrect survey
Silent (off-record) liens (e.g., mechanics’ or estate tax liens)
Pre-existing violations of subdivision laws or zoning ordinances
The policy provides protection from financial loss due to demands that may be made against the title to your home, up to the cost of the title policy. Additionally, it covers:

Payment of legal costs if the title insurer has to defend your title against a covered claim.
Payment of successful claims against the title to your home covered by the policy, up to the cost of the policy.</svelte:fragment>
    </AccordionItem>
    <AccordionItem>
      <svelte:fragment slot="summary">Lender's Policies</svelte:fragment>
      <svelte:fragment slot="content">
A Lender’s policy safeguards the interests of the mortgage holder. In the event of a title fault causing a loss, the mortgage holder will receive compensation. Commonly known as a loan policy, it is issued to mortgage lenders. This policy covers only the amount of the loan, which typically does not equate to the full property value. Normally, the lender wouldn't be concerned about an adverse claim unless the loan becomes nonperforming, and the claim jeopardizes the lender's ability to foreclose and recover its principal and interest. Additionally, in the event of a claim, there is no provision for covering legal expenses for an uninsured party. When issuing a loan policy, the slight extra cost of an owner’s policy is a worthwhile investment.</svelte:fragment>
    </AccordionItem>
