    <AccordionItem>
      <svelte:fragment slot="summary">Deeds</svelte:fragment>
      <svelte:fragment slot="content">Title insurance primarily relies on recorded documents, public records, files, and similar sources. One common document in this process is a deed, which is a written instrument transferring the title or an interest in real property from one party to another. Here are brief descriptions of the most commonly used types of deeds:

General Warranty Deed: This offers the most protection to a real estate buyer. It includes statutory covenants regarding prior conveyance and encumbrance. The seller, or grantor, conveys the property with specific covenants or warranties, legally binding them. These typically include:
a) Covenant of seisin: The grantor warrants ownership of the property and the legal right to convey it.
b) Covenant against encumbrances: The grantor warrants that the property is free of any liens or encumbrances unless specifically stated in the deed.
c) Covenant of quiet enjoyment: The buyer is guaranteed that the title will be good against third parties attempting to establish title to the property.
d) Covenant of further assurance: The grantor promises to deliver any necessary document or instrument to make the title good.

These warranties in a general warranty deed extend back to the origin of the property, making each grantor in the title chain liable for title problems before and during their ownership.

Special Warranty Deed: This type of deed is less protective of the buyer compared to a general warranty deed. The grantor conveys the property with two warranties: (1) They warrant that they have received title, and (2) they warrant that the property was not encumbered during their ownership period unless stated otherwise. The grantor only warrants the title against their own actions or omissions and nothing prior to their ownership.

Quitclaim Deed: This deed conveys any possible interest of the grantor in the property at the date of the deed without representations of encumbrances on title arising from liens, easements, etc. It is commonly used to release an estate or interest less than a "fee" interest.

Deed of Gift: This type of deed can be any of the above types. It is a transfer of title from one person to another without any consideration or money involved. It is generally exempt from grantor’s tax, but there are certain conditions, so it's advisable to consult a title attorney for detailed information.</svelte:fragment>
